{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox monarch | name = Aja | title = [[Maharaja]] of [[Kosala]] | image = | caption = | reign = | coronation = | investiture = | full name = | birth_name = | native_lang1 = | native_lang1_name1 = | native_lang2 = | native_lang2_name1 = | othertitles = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Ayodhya]], [[Kosala|Kingdom of Kosala]] (present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]) | death_place = Ayodhya, Kingdom of Kosala (present-day Uttar Pradesh, India) |succession= [[Maharaja]] of [[Kosala]] | predecessor = [[Raghu]] | heir = | successor =[[Dashratha]] | queen = |spouse-type=Consort(s) | spouse = Indumati | issue = Dashratha | dynasty = [[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]] | father = Raghu | mother = | religion =[[Hinduism]] }} {{Infobox epic character | series = [[Ramayana]] | family = [[Raghu]] (father) Indumati (wife) | children = [[Dasharatha]] }} In Hinduism, '''Aja''' ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: Achan, [[Thai language|Thai]]: Achaban, [[Malay language|Malay]]: Dasarata Raman) was the 38th king in the [[Solar Dynasty]], descent from the sun god [[Surya]]. He was the son of king [[Raghu]], one of the most famous kings of the Ikshvaku dynasty. His paternal grandfather was the pious king [[Dileepa]].
King Aja ruled the kingdom of Kosala on the southern banks of the river [[Sarayu]] in the northern part of [[India]], with [[Ayodhya]] as his capital. His wife Indumati, an [[apsara]] (celestial woman), who was born on earth due to a curse and his son was [[Dasharatha]], father of [[Rama]], an avatar of Vishnu. It is said that Aja was so grief stricken when his wife died, he ran into the palace and committed suicide. Some other instances tell that he couldn't bear the thought of Indumati leaving him and died heart broken that instant. While sage [[Narada]] was traversing the sky, garland from his Veena fell on Indumati, redeeming her from the curse. Regaining the form of [[apsara]], she vanished from earth leaving Aja. King [[Dasharatha]] was only eight months old when Aja died.<ref>http://www.bhriguashram.org/ver3/rama_sister.php</ref>
The classical Indian poet [[Kalidasa]] has elaborated upon the lives and careers of the kings Dileepa, Raghu and Aja in his work entitled ''[[Raghuvaṃśa|Raghuvamsha]]'' (literally: ''"Dynasty of Raghu"''). This is significant as these rulers were the immediate forebears of [[Rama]].
