In [[Inuit mythology]], '''Keelut''' also known as Ke'lets, Qiqion, or Qiqirn,<ref name="Myth Beasts">{{cite web|title=Keelut Mythical Creature|url=http://www.mythicalcreatureslist.com/mythical-creature/Keelut|website=Myth Beasts|publisher=Myth Beasts|accessdate=January 22, 2015}}</ref> is an evil [[chthonic]] [[spirit]] who resembles a hairless dog. It is said to feast upon the dead, and is sometimes seen as a [[wikt:harbinger|harbinger]] of death.<ref>"Keelut Comes to Akliasuk." Norman, Robert. Dalhousie Review; Spring2010, Vol. 90 Issue 1, p75-75, 1p</ref> Having hair only on its feet, the tracks of the Keelut are said to disappear, giving those the creature stalks no warning of its presence.<ref name="Alaska Dispatch News">{{cite news|last1=Toombs|first1=Terrye|title=Alaska folklore: Five mythical creatures of the Last Frontier|url=http://www.adn.com/article/alaska-folklore-five-mythical-creatures-last-frontier|accessdate=January 22, 2015|agency=Alaska Dispatch News|publisher=Alaska Dispatch Publishing|date=June 12, 2012}}</ref>

