'''Kyung-Chik Han''' (1902–2000)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://search.library.utoronto.ca/details?8319747 |title=Kyung-Chik Han collection |website=University of Toronto Libraries |accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> was a [[Koreans|Korean]] [[pastor]] and [[church planter]] and the recipient of the 1992 [[Templeton Prize]] for Progress in Religion.<ref>[http://www.templetonpress.org/sirjohn/templetonprize.asp Templeton Foundation Press: Sir John Templeton] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104073638/http://www.templetonpress.org/sirjohn/templetonprize.asp |date=2008-01-04 }}</ref>  

Born in Kan-ri, [[Pyongwon County|P'yŏngwŏn County]],  [[Korea]], Han graduated from [[Soongsil University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|B. S.]] 1925), the [[College of Emporia]] ([[B. A.]] 1926), and [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] ([[Bachelor of Divinity|B. D.]] 1929).  Ordained in 1933 by the [[Presbyterian Church of Korea]], Han later founded [[Youngnak Presbyterian Church]] in 1945, which he pastored until 1973 and served as a Pastor [[Emeritus]] until his death.  At the time that he received the [[Templeton Prize]], membership of [[Youngnak Presbyterian Church]] had grown to 60,000 and the church had fostered about 500 sister churches worldwide.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE3D9173CF931A25750C0A964958260 CHRONICLE - New York Times<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref>

