'''Oomancy''' (sometimes '''ovomancy''' or '''ooscopy''') refers to [[divination]] by [[Egg (biology)|egg]]s. An example would be the [[oracular]] reading (i.e., [[scrying]]) of the shapes that a [[Separating eggs|separated]] [[egg white]] forms when dropped into hot water. This appears to be similar to methods of [[Molybdomancy|molten lead divination]], which ascribe meaning to the shapes and forms into which hot lead solidifies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museumofwitchcraft.com/displayrecord_mow.php?ObjectNumber=52 |title=Museum Object #52: Copper pan |last= |first= |publisher=[[Museum of Witchcraft]] |accessdate=2 May 2016 |quote=Another form of divination dating from ancient times involved dropping molten lead into a container of cold water from a height. The hot lead hit the water and instantly solidified into all manner of shapes and forms from which the [[Cunning folk in Britain|wise woman]] would make her readings. Sometimes egg white was used instead of lead - safer and cheaper but less impressive. (Adapted from text by [[Cecil Williamson]]).}}</ref>

Along with other young girls of [[Salem Village]], [[Elizabeth Parris]] and [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]] are known to have to [[List of traditional children's games|played]] at reading [[omen]]s by means of an egg and a [[mirror]] (or "Venus glass"): an apparently similar system of egg divination.<ref>Breslaw, Elaine G. (1997). {{Google books|N18JNPG6F5wC|Tituba, Reluctant Witch of Salem: Devilish Indians and Puritan Fantasies|page=89}}.</ref>

